did.unittitle: Ron Howard papers
did.abstract: Collection include photographs (including many campus buildings no longer extant) and slides (including commencements, buildings, distinguished alumni, President Lloyd Elliott, Jack Friedenthal, Edward "Skip" Ghnem, the GW mascot, Elmer Kayser, the men's and Women's basketball teams, President Trachtenberg, the University Yard, Gates, campus and Washington scenes, and other personalities. Artifacts include banners, key chains, buttons, towels, medals, tickets to Ronald Reagan Honorary Degree ceremony, videotapes, including Alumni Weekend, 1985, Reagan convocation, commencements, Walter Cronkite, Recruiting tapes and an award given to Ronald Howard. The collection spans the years 1958-99.

prefercite.head: Preferred citation
prefercite.p: Ron Howard papers, University Archives, Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: The collection was donated to University Archives by Alumni House in 1999, following the death of Mr. Howard.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Ronald Warren Howard (1934-August 19, 1999) came to GW in 1964 as a counselor in the Admissions Office, and would serve the university for over thirty years, until his death in 1999 following a six year battle with cancer. Howard graduated from Central College in Pella, Iowa (B.A. in English, 1956) and worked as an admissions counselor at Carthage College in Kenosha, Wisconsin before taking a similar position here. At GW he became assistant director of admissions and foreign students admissions officer before moving to the Development Office, where he served as director of alumni support from 1973-80. In September 1980 he began work in the Alumni Office as associate director of alumni relations. He served as Director of Alumni Relations from June 1986-1989, and then became the first full-time director of the Alumni Admissions Program, which mobilized volunteer alumni nationwide to help recruit prospective GW students from their particular regions.

Ron Howard traveled the country spreading the message of GW to prospective students, as well as alumni. He was such an enthusiastic ambassador of the university that he became known as "Mr. GW" and "Mr. Alumni." Howard won the GW Award in 1977, given in "special recognition to those people who have made The George Washington University a better place to be." Ron Howard was an enthusiastic photographer. He free lanced for the student newspaper the Hatchet, and some of his images appeared in various campus publications as well. His enthusiasm to capture through the lens of a camera the people and events surrounding the university has been a benefit to the preservation of GW's history.
(Biographical information compiled from "GW Magazine" article, Fall 1993 and "By George" article September 7, 1999)

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The collections consists of five series: photographs, slides, memorabilia, videotapes, and personal awards, etc. from Ron Howard.

Materials in this collection include photographs (including many campus buildings no longer extant) and slides (including commencements, buildings, distinguished alumni, President Lloyd Elliott, Jack Friedenthal, Edward "Skip" Ghnem, the GW mascot, Elmer Kayser, the men's and Women's basketball teams, President Trachtenberg, the University Yard, Gates, campus and Washington scenes, and other personalities. Artifacts include banners, key chains, buttons, towels, medals, tickets to Ronald Reagan Honorary Degree ceremony, videotapes, including Alumni Weekend, 1985, Reagan convocation, commencements, Walter Cronkite, Recruiting tapes and an award given to Ronald Howard. The collection spans the years 1958-99.

The collection came to the archives with very liitle order to it, and almost no items identified by Mr. Howard. Every effort was made to correctly identify people and events, and assign a date range, although at times this was difficult to do. Photos and slides of particular events were sorted and kept in the same folder/tray, but some images may actually belong to other events. Years have been assigned using clues from the images themselves (for example the date on the back of the photo or slide, or the cover of a Commencement program someone might be holding in a photo), but most of the dates are approximations.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in five series: Photographs, Slides, Memorabilia, Videotapes, and Certificates and awards.

did.unittitle: Photographs

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of 5,000 images. They range in date from c.1975-c.1998, with the bulk from 1985-1998. The series is arranged alphabetically by subject headings such as Basketball, Commencements, Distinguished Alumni Award Winners (which may also have photos of the winter commencement for that year, and include Honorary Degree recipients), GW Presidents Lloyd Elliott and Stephen Joel Trachtenberg, and various specific events (including alumni gatherings, Walter Mondale's campaign visit to GW in 1984, Bob Hope's visit in 1985, and the 1990 summit with President Bush and Mikhail.) Mr. Howard also took photos of celebrities such as Jerry Lewis, Cokie Roberts, Walter Cronkite and Robert Redford, and politicians such as Marion Barry, Dick Gephardt, Dan Quayle, and Walter Mondale.

Mr. Howard's personal photos were varied and many, and a sampling has been maintained as a sub-series. These are generally photos not linked to the university or unidentifiable, and includes individuals, vacation trips, and Howard's life before coming to GW.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of awards and certificates and miscellaneous personal items of Ron Howard. Certificates from fraternities include Phi Sigma Kappa, and Omicron Delta Kappa. Awards include those given to Howard for his 20, 25, and 30 years of service to GW, as well as his 1977 GW Award, given in "special recognition to those people who have made The George Washington University a better place to be." Also in this series are photos of Howard receiving his GW Award in 1977, a letter of thanks from President Trachtenberg for the work Howard did on his Inauguration, and a souvenir book of the Basketball Hall of Fame, which includes Red Auerbach, former coach of the Boston Celtics and GW Class of 1940.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series compliment the photos and are contained in 6 trays (1.0 linear foot), or approximately 3,000 images. They range in date from 1958-83, with the bulk from 1970-80. The series is arranged alphabetically by subject and vary somewhat from the photo series. Major subjects include Basketball (from 1968-1983), Buildings (including Bacon Hall, Gelman Library, Marvin Center, Rice Hall), Commencements, Distinguished Alumni Award Winners, Drama at the Marvin Theater, GW's 150th Anniversary, Individuals (including GW faculty Marcus Cunliffe, John Latimer, Elmer Kayser, John Boswell) Student/Campus Scenes, Personalities (including Muhammad Ali, Pearl Bailey, Neil Armstrong, Everett Dirksen, Gerald Ford, Herbert Hoover, Harry Truman, Robert and Ted Kennedy, Queen Elizabeth, Ronald Reagan, Elizabeth Taylor, Earl Warren).

The Washington Scenes sub-series contains subjects including Arlington Cemetery and John F. Kennedy's gravesite, the Capitol, 4th of July fireworks on the Mall, the Jefferson and Lincoln Memorials, and the White House. It also contains scenes from the NBC news program "Meet the Press," with guests dating from 1965-1975.
The final sub-series contains Mr. Howard's personal slides (as with the photo series), and features approximately 100 images from a trip he took to the former U.S.S.R. in 1983.
